data.title: Enhancement suggestion: Make non-printing control-character (etc.) constants visible
data.body:
1. I don't know if this Enhancement Suggestion belongs in atom/atom or in atom/language-ruby.  I do suspect that this enhancement also applies to other languages such as Python, Perl, etc., not exclusively to Ruby; given its display-oriented nature, it does seem (to me) to be Atom/core rather than syntax/language- (Ruby-) dependent.
2. See attached screenshots for comparison between what Sublime Text 3 does and what Atom does not yet do... but should.  These two screenshots show exactly the same file/lines of code in both Atom and in Sublime Text.  The Atom screenshot was taken in v1.1, but the same behavior exists in v1.3 (my current Atom).
3. In Ruby (also in other languages), a constant (or variable) can be declared as at Line 31 (in both screenshots), for example a constant ESC (an "Escape" character code) which has a single character code (integer) value.  Other instances of this sort of thing would include CSI (Control Sequence Introducer), SI (Shift-In), SO (Shift-Out) char-code values, etc.

Once declared, Sublime Text will render a graphic, e.g., a reverse-video'd "ESC" wherever that character-code value occurs in subsequent character strings... Atom does not.

See Lines 32--59 for the Sublime Text screenshot, which clearly shows "ANSI Escape Sequence" strings of characters (including in comments!) -- the corresponding lines in the Atom screenshot do not, thus implying that these "ANSI Escape Sequence" characters strings are malformed and missing the leading ESC character.
1. Suggestion/request is to enhance Atom (or syntax/language packages, especially Ruby) to recognize such character-code constants (&/or variables) and render them visibly as part(s) of character strings where these occur (mimicking Sublime Text in this regard).
2. My environment/versions:
   $ atom -v
   1.3.0
   $ uname -a
   Linux alikot 3.13.0-74-generic #118-Ubuntu SMP Thu Dec 17 22:52:10 UTC 2015 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux
3. Sample screenshots: Atom (#1) and Sublime Text (#2)
   ![rubyconstants-in-atom-v1-1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1362449/12023462/f1c5de60-ad56-11e5-8c99-181fed03082f.png)
   ![rubyconstants-in-sublimetext3](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1362449/12023461/f1c35cd0-ad56-11e5-9cfc-38c17d3e0513.png)

Thank you for your kind consideration and any guidance...

data.title: Atom executable segfaults if Atom is already running
data.body:
I'm using Atom 1.3.2 from the official RPM on Fedora 22.

When Atom is already running, if I run atom as a command from a shell, I get a crash, although Atom seems to make a second window:

```
$ atom
$ /usr/bin/atom: line 113: 25674 Segmentation fault      (core dumped) nohup "$ATOM_PATH" --executed-from="$(pwd)" --pid=$$ "$@" > "$ATOM_HOME/nohup.out" 2>&1
App load time: 120ms
Failed to get crash dump id.
Report Id:
```

How to repro:
Run `/usr/share/atom/atom` from one terminal. After atom pops up, repeat from another terminal. The second run results in a second window and the crash message. This is the simplest error case involving the binary and not the script. This involves `brightray::URLRequestContextGetter::GetURLRequestContext()` just like https://github.com/atom/electron/issues/591

data.title: Look into VS Code editor implementation (Improve editor performance)
data.body:
Hi,

I have been following the latest versions of Atom and VS Code (looking for ST replacement).

'Ideologically' I would prefer Atom because it is 'more' open source and seems much more flexible compared to VS code. However, performance, especially UX performance has always been the major factor stopping me from switching from ST (I am guessing that I am not alone in this)

And at the moment it seems like VS Code has the edge in that respect. Its editor has better performance compared to Atom.

For example, when I test the _Find_ command in  this file: https://github.com/YemSalat/spark-lang/blob/master/src/parser/parser.js

And search for things like 'peg', 'this', etc. A clean install of Atom takes between _1s - 1.5s_, while VS Code does it almost instantly (I would say no more then _250ms_). It is also much better at 'live-updating' the search results as you are typing. I am testing this on a 3 year old i5 8GB laptop.

I think looking into their implementation could be helpful, as in my opinion improving editor performance can highly increase the editor adoption rates among developers who have not made the switch yet.

PS The VS Code editor can be found here: https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/tree/master/src/vs/editor

data.title: seti-monokai theme should be removed from Atom Packages
data.body:
It can not install the seti-monokai theme because the author removed the repository. It's no longer available on github (see author's page @joaoafrmartins), but he is still available for download.

**Reproduction Steps:**
1. Go to preferences
2. Go to install section
3. Search for "monokai"
4. Try install seti-monokai theme
5. Go to themes section
6. Click in _show output_ and see explanation

**Expected behavior:**

the theme be installed

**Observed behavior:**

Theme not installed, but still available for download. Error below:

```
Installing “seti-monokai@0.3.1” failed.Hide output…
Unable to download https://www.atom.io/api/packages/seti-monokai/versions/0.3.1/tarball: 
400 Bad Request Repository inaccessible
```
